Everything is already prepared — Bicep templates, GitHub Actions, workflows. Here's the exact deployment sequence:

Step 1 — Prerequisites (one-time)

# Install Azure CLI if not already installed
brew install azure-cli

# Log in
az login

# Confirm correct subscription
az account show --query "{name:name, id:id}" -o table

# If wrong subscription:
az account set --subscription "<your subscription id>"
Step 2 — Create resource group + ACR

az group create --name servisite-rg --location uksouth

# Create Container Registry (must exist before Bicep deploy)
az acr create \
  --resource-group servisite-rg \
  --name servisite \
  --sku Basic \
  --admin-enabled false
Step 3 — Deploy infrastructure (Bicep)
The parameters.json has Key Vault references that won't exist yet, so pass secrets directly for the first deploy:


cd /Users/kumaran/work/ServiSite/infrastructure/bicep

az deployment group create \
  --resource-group servisite-rg \
  --template-file main.bicep \
  --parameters parameters.json \
  --parameters \
    dbPassword='<strong-password>' \
    jwtSecret='<random-32-char-string>' \
    revalidateSecret='<random-string>' \
    internalSecret='<random-string>'
This creates: VNet, PostgreSQL, Redis, Key Vault, App Service (backend + frontend), Front Door + WAF, Blob Storage. Takes ~10–15 minutes.

Step 4 — Set up OIDC for GitHub Actions

# Get your subscription and tenant IDs
az account show --query "{subscriptionId:id, tenantId:tenantId}" -o table

# Create the service principal (app registration)
az ad app create --display-name "servisite-github-actions"

# Note the appId from the output, then:
APP_ID="<appId from above>"

az ad sp create --id $APP_ID

# Assign Contributor role on the resource group
az role assignment create \
  --assignee $APP_ID \
  --role Contributor \
  --scope /subscriptions/$(az account show --query id -o tsv)/resourceGroups/servisite-rg

# Also grant AcrPush role for Container Registry
az role assignment create \
  --assignee $APP_ID \
  --role AcrPush \
  --scope $(az acr show --name servisite --query id -o tsv)

# Create federated credential for GitHub Actions (main branch)
az ad app federated-credential create \
  --id $APP_ID \
  --parameters '{
    "name": "servisite-github-main",
    "issuer": "https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com",
    "subject": "repo:<your-github-username>/ServiSite:ref:refs/heads/main",
    "audiences": ["api://AzureADMultiApp"]
  }'
Step 5 — Add GitHub Secrets
Go to your repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret:

Secret	Value
AZURE_CLIENT_ID	The appId from Step 4
AZURE_TENANT_ID	Your tenant ID from Step 4
AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID	Your subscription ID from Step 4
ACR_LOGIN_SERVER	servisite.azurecr.io
Step 6 — Run Prisma migration on production DB
After Bicep deploys, get the DB connection string from Key Vault or App Service config, then:


# Temporary: run migration via a one-off command (use the prod DATABASE_URL)
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://..." npx prisma migrate deploy
Or connect via the App Service console in Azure Portal and run it there.

Step 7 — DNS in IONOS
After Bicep deploys, get the Front Door hostname:


az afd endpoint show \
  --resource-group servisite-rg \
  --profile-name servisite-prod-fd \
  --endpoint-name servisite \
  --query hostName -o tsv
Then in IONOS DNS for servisite.co.uk:

Type	Name	Value
ALIAS	@	<front-door-hostname>.azurefd.net
CNAME	www	<front-door-hostname>.azurefd.net
CNAME	*	<front-door-hostname>.azurefd.net
Step 8 — First deploy
Push to main or trigger manually:


# Trigger backend workflow
gh workflow run backend.yml

# Trigger frontend workflow  
gh workflow run frontend.yml
Or just push a commit to main — both workflows trigger automatically on changes to their respective directories.

