  Good question. These manual commands are one-time patches because the Bicep deploy was never run — the App Services were created by GitHub Actions (which only deploys containers), but the full infrastructure (role assignments, access restrictions) was never set up by Bicep.

What should have happened:


az deployment group create ... (Bicep)
  → Creates App Services
  → Grants AcrPull role automatically
  → Sets correct X-Azure-FDID restriction automatically
  → Everything works on first deploy
What actually happened:

App Services were created manually/partially
Bicep was never run
So we're patching each missing piece manually
For a fresh environment (dev, staging, or redo prod):

You just run ONE command:


az deployment group create \
  --resource-group servisite-rg \
  --template-file infrastructure/bicep/main.bicep \
  --parameters @infrastructure/bicep/parameters.json \
  --parameters \
    dbPassword='...' \
    jwtSecret='...' \
    revalidateSecret='...' \
    internalSecret='...'

    That single command creates everything — VNet, subnets, PostgreSQL, Redis, Key Vault, Storage, App Services, AcrPull roles, access restrictions, Front Door — all in one go. No manual patching needed.

